  "nursesNote": "Several anticonvulsants are used as mood stabilizers in bipolar disorder when lithium is not ideal. Valproate (divalproex/valproic acid) can be hepatotoxic and lower platelets, so the nurse monitors liver function, platelet counts, and drug levels. Carbamazepine can suppress blood cell counts (agranulocytosis/aplastic anemia) and cause a severe rash, so the nurse monitors the CBC and watches for rash. Lamotrigine carries a risk of a serious rash (Stevens-Johnson syndrome), so it is titrated slowly and any rash is reported immediately. For all of these, the patient takes the drug daily and does not stop abruptly, has regular labs, and is counseled that these drugs are teratogenic. The nurse teaches the patient to report any rash, easy bruising or bleeding, yellowing of the skin, or fever.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Monitor liver function and platelets on valproate",
    "Monitor the CBC on carbamazepine",
    "Report any rash immediately on lamotrigine and titrate slowly",
    "Teach daily adherence and not stopping abruptly",
    "Counsel about teratogenic risk and report rash, bruising, or jaundice"
  ],
